{"term":"2011","caseName":"Martel v. Clair","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/2011/10-1265","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - December 06, 2011","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/roberts6/oral_argument_audio/22535","transcript":[{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll hear argument first this morning in Case 10-1265, Martel v. Clair.","start":0,"stop":7.42,"duration":7.42},{"text":"Mr. Campbell.","start":7.42,"stop":8.304,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:","start":8.304,"stop":12.074,"duration":3.77},{"text":"For 12 years, Mr. Clair's Federal habeas corpus petition was litigated in the Federal district court in front of the same Federal district court judge.","start":12.074,"stop":20.663,"duration":8.59},{"text":"His petition raised 39 challenges to his guilt and penalty, and the judge oversaw years of discovery, presided over a 2-day evidentiary hearing, and received extensive briefing.","start":20.663,"stop":31.219,"duration":10.56},{"text":"When the case was under submission, Mr. Clair sent a letter to the judge expressing dissatisfaction with his team of attorneys from the Federal Public Defender's office, and requested that they be replaced.","start":31.219,"stop":42.593,"duration":11.37},{"text":"The judge asked both sides' counsel for their position on Clair's complaint.","start":42.593,"stop":46.645,"duration":4.05},{"text":"The Federal Public Defender responded that, after conferring with their client, Mr. Clair was willing to continue with them for that point.","start":46.645,"stop":54.318,"duration":7.67},{"text":"The court then stated it would take no further action.","start":54.318,"stop":57.103,"duration":2.79},{"text":"3 months later, just before the court was to issue its decision in the case, Clair complained again.","start":57.103,"stop":63.09,"duration":5.99},{"text":"The court issued a written order--","start":63.09,"stop":65.025,"duration":1.94}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Was there some way that Clair knew that the court was just about to issue its decision?","start":65.025,"stop":69.41,"duration":4.38}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"--I think, Your Honor, the only way to be sure was the fact that at some point, as I understand it, the district court judge had announced the day he would be retiring, which would be June 30th of 2005.","start":69.41,"stop":80.468,"duration":11.06},{"text":"So, there's probably an inference there that it could be expected that the decision was going to be coming out by the end of the -- end of June 2005.","start":80.468,"stop":88.056,"duration":7.59}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"There was a deadline set for all submissions, wasn't there?","start":88.056,"stop":91.274,"duration":3.22}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"There was an initial deadline set for the filing of the briefing, post-evidentiary hearing briefing, and there would be no extensions of time.","start":91.274,"stop":100.966,"duration":9.69},{"text":"Subsequently, there was in fact another submission by Mr. Clair in May of 2005 with some additional declarations.","start":100.966,"stop":108.202,"duration":7.24},{"text":"The court accepted those declarations, but made it clear it would accept no additional submissions in the case unless it ordered otherwise, that it would proceed with the decision.","start":108.202,"stop":116.225,"duration":8.02},{"text":"Once upon -- anyway, in June, June 16th, 2005, Mr. Clair sent a second complaint about his counsel again, and the district court issued a written order denying that request, finding that Clair's counsel was doing a proper job and did not appear to have a conflict of interest.","start":116.225,"stop":136.222,"duration":20},{"text":"The district court had an excellent factual basis for that conclusion because it had just concluded work on its extensive order denying the petition in Mr. Clair's case.","start":136.222,"stop":145.66,"duration":9.44}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"But this petition had something new, the report that his investigator had turned up this evidence.","start":145.66,"stop":153.014,"duration":7.35}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, Your Honor.","start":153.014,"stop":154.699,"duration":1.69},{"text":"The -- what Mr. Clair's complaint indicated, there was some additional physical evidence that had not been examined or investigated before.","start":154.699,"stop":162.286,"duration":7.59},{"text":"He indicated that the Federal Public Defender actually had met with the Orange County law enforcement about the evidence, and he was upset that there was no further action being taken by the Federal Public Defender regarding testing, seeking DNA testing or testing of that evidence.","start":162.286,"stop":178.315,"duration":16.03}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"There has been some additional litigation regarding this physical evidence since this -- the time of -- of the unsuccessful substitution request, hasn't there been?","start":178.315,"stop":187.503,"duration":9.19}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":187.503,"stop":188.486,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Could you tell us what has happened with that?","start":188.486,"stop":190.872,"duration":2.39}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry?","start":190.872,"stop":191.672,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry.","start":191.672,"stop":192.122,"duration":0.45},{"text":"Could you tell us what has us what has happened with that litigation?","start":192.122,"stop":194.424,"duration":2.3}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"The status of that litigation: Once the -- the petition was denied, Mr. Clair filed a notice -- there was a notice of appeal filed by the Federal Public Defender.","start":194.424,"stop":204.546,"duration":10.12},{"text":"Mr. Clair also filed a notice of appeal because of the denial of his substitution motion.","start":204.546,"stop":208.584,"duration":4.04},{"text":"Those were merged together.","start":208.584,"stop":210.35,"duration":1.77},{"text":"Mr. Clair was appointed new counsel.","start":210.35,"stop":212.469,"duration":2.12},{"text":"The new counsel then filed a rule -- a rule -- a request to the district court to entertain a Rule 60(b) motion, which the district court denied.","start":212.469,"stop":221.842,"duration":9.37},{"text":"The Ninth Circuit ordered that the district court consider the Rule 60(b) motion.","start":221.842,"stop":225.878,"duration":4.04},{"text":"The district court heard the Rule 60(b) motion and then denied it.","start":225.878,"stop":229.763,"duration":3.89},{"text":"$Mr. Clair then filed a protective petition, a petition for writ of habeas corpus for a successive petition, with the Ninth Circuit, and has also filed a petition for writ of habeas corpus with the California Supreme Court.","start":229.763,"stop":242.421,"duration":12.66}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what I was referring to.","start":242.421,"stop":243.423,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":243.423,"stop":243.79,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And what -- what has happened there?","start":243.79,"stop":245.057,"duration":1.27},{"text":"Was there -- was there testing of this evidence in connection with that?","start":245.057,"stop":248.325,"duration":3.27}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"There -- there had been -- there has been some testing of the evidence during -- during that time by the Orange County law enforcement in regards to its relationship to the crime, or its relationship to another crime that occurred at that time, which I think that information is set forth in the appendix to the opposition to the petition for certiorari.","start":248.325,"stop":268.138,"duration":19.81},{"text":"The--","start":268.138,"stop":270.407,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry.","start":270.407,"stop":271.09,"duration":0.68},{"text":"Can you remind me of what the outcome of that testing was?","start":271.09,"stop":274.376,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"--The -- the outcome of -- of the testing is that, to the extent that the testing was done to see if the -- there was any DNA matching between the other murder that had occurred a couple days before and the murder of Ms. Rodgers -- let's see if I can say this succinctly.","start":274.376,"stop":292.604,"duration":18.23},{"text":"The -- there was -- there was no matching of Mr. Clair's DNA with anything from the murder scene of the Rodgers murder, and there was no matching of any DNA that was found for the perpetrator of the other murder at the site of Ms. Rodgers' murder.","start":292.604,"stop":309.482,"duration":16.88}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Counsel, as I read your briefs, I think you're making, perhaps, two different arguments.","start":309.482,"stop":319.071,"duration":9.59},{"text":"And I want to focus you in on which one you are really concentrating on.","start":319.071,"stop":326.077,"duration":7.01}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":326.077,"stop":326.611,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Which is, this presentation seems to be that, regardless of what standard we apply to the court of appeals review of what the district court did in denying the motion to substitute counsel, that it was wrong.","start":326.611,"stop":341.004,"duration":14.39},{"text":"And I presume that means it was wrong for the standard you are proposing and it was wrong for the interest of justice standard, am I correct?","start":341.004,"stop":350.192,"duration":9.19}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- yes, Your Honor.","start":350.192,"stop":351.442,"duration":1.25},{"text":"I think under any standard that would apply, we think that the -- that the Ninth Circuit's disposition is incorrect.","start":351.442,"stop":356.677,"duration":5.24}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":356.677,"stop":357.044,"duration":0.37},{"text":"As I read the Ninth Circuit's decision, assuming an interest of justice standard because that's the one they invoked, they said what happened here is that the district court didn't hold a hearing to determine itself exactly what the dispute was about, and so it was a process failure, basically is what they're saying.","start":357.044,"stop":382.127,"duration":25.08},{"text":"Now, you make assumptions based on matters that have come up since that hearing about what the dispute was about and -- but I still don't know what the Federal defender's position was as to whether or not communications had broken down with the client to a point where they thought, as they did on appeal, that they couldn't continue.","start":382.127,"stop":408.276,"duration":26.15},{"text":"So, tell me why, assuming we accept that an interest of justice standard applies, the circuit court has no power or applied it improperly by saying -- forget about the remedy -- has no power to say, district court judges, you have to at a minimum inquire and set forth your reasons based on the facts of that inquiry.","start":408.276,"stop":436.628,"duration":28.35}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":436.628,"stop":436.978,"duration":0.35},{"text":"And the reason is that, looking at the record and what was presented to the Federal district court at the time it received the request by Mr. Clair in June of 2005, what Mr. Clair's allegation was was that he disagreed with the investigative, tactical, strategic decisions that were being made by the Federal Public Defender.","start":436.978,"stop":459.543,"duration":22.57},{"text":"That -- that was the reason that was in Mr. Clair's -- Mr. Clair's allegation.","start":459.543,"stop":464.864,"duration":5.32},{"text":"Those premises, even--","start":464.864,"stop":466.581,"duration":1.72}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"But what does that have to do with","start":466.581,"stop":468.149,"duration":1.57},{"text":"\"I think they are doing a good? \"","start":468.149,"stop":469.582,"duration":1.43},{"text":"\"I mean, it -- it could well be that the judge later decides, after he hears from the Federal defender, I don't think that -- we don't think there is anything to be done, he disagrees. \"","start":469.582,"stop":481.238,"duration":11.66},{"text":"\"But he really never got an explanation from the Federal defenders. \"","start":481.238,"stop":485.942,"duration":4.7}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"--I'm sorry--","start":485.942,"stop":487.108,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"He never got an explanation from the Federal defenders.","start":487.108,"stop":490.245,"duration":3.14}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"--Your Honor, it in fact -- it would be -- it's appropriate -- if the record -- if the allegations of the -- of the Petitioner and the record before the court is sufficient for the court to make the finding that there is in fact no basis for substitution, it is not necessary for the court to go ahead and conduct an inquiry or a hearing or to initiate other further process in the case; and the allegation here which went to the physical evidence in the case from the standpoint of the evidence in this case, and the way this case is prosecuted, and the evidence of Mr. Clair's guilt, the fact that there was additional physical evidence that might be available, simply wouldn't have supported any cognizable claims in the Federal habeas corpus action.","start":490.245,"stop":535.624,"duration":45.38},{"text":"There was no need for any further investigation or inquiry on the part of the court based on what was presented to it at the time.","start":535.624,"stop":541.528,"duration":5.9}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What about a -- a possible Brady claim?","start":541.528,"stop":543.63,"duration":2.1},{"text":"Is there a disagreement about whether this physical evidence could have been tested at the -- and revealed anything at the time of the trial?","start":543.63,"stop":551.9,"duration":8.27}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"There I have to -- I think I have to take what the Ninth Circuit says in its opinion about this case, which is what we have here is physical evidence that could be subject to forensic testing now that was not available in 1987.","start":551.9,"stop":567.246,"duration":15.35},{"text":"So the fact that there might be later -- there might have been developments in forensic techniques since 1987 when Mr. Clair's trial occurred, doesn't support any claim of trial error back in 1987.","start":567.246,"stop":579.736,"duration":12.49},{"text":"You can't show any prejudice from any -- from any failure back in 1987 because the testing wasn't available to do that they now want to do.","start":579.736,"stop":587.157,"duration":7.42}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What about an actual innocence claim?","start":587.157,"stop":589.759,"duration":2.6}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, an actual innocence claim, I think to begin with, it wouldn't be clear, based on this Court's jurisprudence at the time, that a factual innocence claim would be cognizable in this Federal habeas corpus proceeding.","start":589.759,"stop":602.167,"duration":12.41},{"text":"It would be a -- this Court has indicated to the -- has never really actually held that that is a cognizable claim.","start":602.167,"stop":608.906,"duration":6.74},{"text":"Even if it -- it did, it wouldn't be an exhausted, it would certainly be an unexhausted claim.","start":608.906,"stop":614.057,"duration":5.15},{"text":"California in fact does entertain that type of claim, does provide a State avenue for that type of claim.","start":614.057,"stop":619.211,"duration":5.15},{"text":"There is plenty of reasons why you would not raise that claim at this point, especially at the end of the process of the first Federal habeas corpus petition.","start":619.211,"stop":626.55,"duration":7.34}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"You are familiar with 3599(e), aren't you?","start":626.55,"stop":631.519,"duration":4.97}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":631.519,"stop":632.438,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Which requires counsel to participate in subsequent proceedings.","start":632.438,"stop":638.175,"duration":5.74}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":638.175,"stop":639.592,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Of a certain type and limited.","start":639.592,"stop":641.044,"duration":1.45},{"text":"Is it your position that if there is a complete breakdown of communications with an attorney, post habeas decision, that that is inadequate in the interest of justice or otherwise for a court to say, that could implicate proceedings after 3599, so I should substitute now?","start":641.044,"stop":663.99,"duration":22.95}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"Actually, Your Honor, yes, it is.","start":663.99,"stop":666.609,"duration":2.62},{"text":"At that point the defendant has, of course, already gone through the trial, the State appeal, and the State habeas process, as -- particularly at the State trial and the State appellate process, of course, the standard for substitution of counsel is the potential total breakdown of communications, the irreconcilable conflict, conflict of interest.","start":666.609,"stop":687.939,"duration":21.33},{"text":"By the time you've gone through the entire process by which you have gone through the State trial, you have exhausted your claims in State court--","start":687.939,"stop":695.528,"duration":7.59}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, but you are presuming you are going to win.","start":695.528,"stop":697.046,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"--Excuse me?","start":697.046,"stop":697.796,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"You are presuming you are going to win.","start":697.796,"stop":699.08,"duration":1.28},{"text":"I think 3599 applies to situations in which the habeas petitioner wins a remand or otherwise has something that's going to follow the habeas decision.","start":699.08,"stop":712.223,"duration":13.14}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, the -- the point is is that by the time you have reached that juncture, in which the claims have been raised and litigated multiple times in multiple forums, that the need for the type of communication and contact that occurs at the trial and State appellate level is not as essential or necessary at that juncture.","start":712.223,"stop":734.503,"duration":22.28}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose -- suppose the public defender had said to the district court what it said to the Ninth Circuit, and that is that the attorney-client relationship has broken down to such an extent that substitution would be appropriate, which wasn't asked.","start":734.503,"stop":752.967,"duration":18.46},{"text":"But suppose the public defender had given Would the district that answer to the district judge.","start":752.967,"stop":757.269,"duration":4.3},{"text":"judge still have rightly denied the motion for substitution?","start":757.269,"stop":765.358,"duration":8.09}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, he would have, especially given that the case at that point was completely under submission and simply awaiting for decision.","start":765.358,"stop":771.862,"duration":6.5},{"text":"At that point there is in fact no more litigation to be occurring, the -- whatever the problem with communication is at that point is not going to in any way adversely affect the -- the representation.","start":771.862,"stop":785.269,"duration":13.41},{"text":"The case is over.","start":785.269,"stop":786.271,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"If I understand your answers to some of these questions, you are not at all relying on the fact that the district court had made this decision 2 months earlier.","start":786.271,"stop":796.31,"duration":10.04},{"text":"You think that the answer would be the same had the district court not made an inquiry 2 months earlier; is that correct?","start":796.31,"stop":803.497,"duration":7.19}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that is correct.","start":803.497,"stop":805.599,"duration":2.1},{"text":"I mean, if -- yes.","start":805.599,"stop":807.601,"duration":2},{"text":"That -- that is an extra fact in this case, but I don't think that's the pivotal fact as far as what the district court has done as far as exercising its direction -- its discretion in June when it received the complaint from Mr. -- Mr. Clair.","start":807.601,"stop":820.508,"duration":12.91}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"So when is a district court required to engage in some kind of inquiry?","start":820.508,"stop":826.679,"duration":6.17}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, when the -- when the allegation is made that -- by the petitioner that he has, in fact, been denied what he is entitled to under 3599, which is the appointment and representation by counsel qualified under that statute.","start":826.679,"stop":844.224,"duration":17.55}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I was, again assuming as Justice Sotomayor was, that if we're in an interest of justice world, if that's the appropriate standard, when is the district -- when does the district court have to make an inquiry, and what kind of inquiry does he have to make?","start":844.224,"stop":858.65,"duration":14.43}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- the inquiry -- the inquiry would occur when an allegation was made that, for whatever reason, the counsel does not meet the qualifications that are expected to be met, the counsel has a adverse conflict of interest, or counsel has basically reached a point where he is no longer representing or acting as an advocate for--","start":858.65,"stop":881.416,"duration":22.77}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you're -- I thought that that test was an alternative to the interest of justice standard.","start":881.416,"stop":885.218,"duration":3.8},{"text":"I am positing that the interest of justice standard applies and you are giving me back those same three factors.","start":885.218,"stop":892.122,"duration":6.9},{"text":"Do you think that that is all the interest of justice standard is about?","start":892.122,"stop":895.257,"duration":3.13}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"--I think in the context of the Federal habeas corpus action, that is in fact -- in which there is a statutory right to counsel -- that is in fact the interest -- where the interest of justice standard would be.","start":895.257,"stop":906.814,"duration":11.56},{"text":"The interest of--","start":906.814,"stop":908.316,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"So this is sort of a made-up standard.","start":908.316,"stop":910.283,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"--No--","start":910.283,"stop":911.451,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Can you point to one case in which this standard has been used by any district court or court of appeals?","start":911.451,"stop":919.791,"duration":8.34}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"--No, I cannot.","start":919.791,"stop":921.224,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Can you point to any inquiry by Congress in which such a test was discussed, considered in any way?","start":921.224,"stop":931.849,"duration":10.63}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I cannot.","start":931.849,"stop":933.115,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Where did you get it from?","start":933.115,"stop":934.884,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"It's actually analogous to the way this Court over the years has divided up the jurisprudence regarding the Sixth Amendment right to counsel and the dividing line between claims of ineffective assistance of counsel and claims of denial of counsel.","start":934.884,"stop":949.976,"duration":15.09}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, so what you're suggesting is in noncapital cases, which are less serious, you are going to have a higher bar for a right that the statute gives a judge without any limitation.","start":949.976,"stop":967.438,"duration":17.46},{"text":"The capital limitation is that the judge on its own motion or a motion by defendant can substitute.","start":967.438,"stop":975.376,"duration":7.94}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"No, we're not in the context of a noncapital habeas.","start":975.376,"stop":978.661,"duration":3.28},{"text":"There has never been any construction, certainly by this Court, of what \"interest of justice\" means in the context of substitution of counsel, of a statutory counsel, in the context of either capital or noncapital habeas.","start":978.661,"stop":994.022,"duration":15.36}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"So how about a standard that the courts are used to and one that has a basis in Congress's choice, like interest of justice?","start":994.022,"stop":1005.747,"duration":11.72}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, actually, Your Honor, I think we have in fact, to the extent we are analogizing to what this Court has long done as far as dividing question of Sixth Amendment claims between ineffective assistance of counsel and denial of counsel.","start":1005.747,"stop":1019.238,"duration":13.49},{"text":"We are in fact submitting a concept that is actually very familiar to this Court and very similar to what this Court deals with in many Sixth Amendment claims.","start":1019.238,"stop":1027.76,"duration":8.52},{"text":"We are simply looking at it in the context now of the fact that you have been given or entitled, a statutory entitlement to be represented by counsel, you are entitled to protect that right to the extent to vindicate that particular right, which is to be appointed that counsel.","start":1027.76,"stop":1043.855,"duration":16.1},{"text":"If you are denied that right, then you in fact have a legitimate reason to ask for new counsel, for new counsel to be appointed.","start":1043.855,"stop":1050.526,"duration":6.67},{"text":"The interest of justice standard doesn't have a fixed meaning, really, in any context.","start":1050.526,"stop":1055.344,"duration":4.82}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"It doesn't have a fixed meaning.","start":1055.344,"stop":1057.013,"duration":1.67},{"text":"I mean wouldn't you think -- I suspect the answer is you do think -- that -- a district judge has a lot of power in many, many areas and in one of those areas some district judge sometimes could make a horrendous mistake that really wrecks a case, and in such a matter the court of appeals if it sees a really horrendous error will probably have the authority to say you went beyond whatever standard applies, at least here, at least -- okay, we agree on that one.","start":1057.013,"stop":1088.901,"duration":31.89},{"text":"So they use some words, \"effectiveness\" and whatever the words are, \"interest of justice\", just to reflect that fact.","start":1088.901,"stop":1095.405,"duration":6.5},{"text":"I mean, that's what I think what happens.","start":1095.405,"stop":1097.59,"duration":2.18},{"text":"And your complaint is he didn't abuse his -- he didn't really abuse anything, he made a good decision, the district judge.","start":1097.59,"stop":1104.761,"duration":7.17},{"text":"Isn't that what that comes down to?","start":1104.761,"stop":1106.428,"duration":1.67}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"That is certainly an aspect of the complaint.","start":1106.428,"stop":1109.48,"duration":3.05},{"text":"But to us what's very important--","start":1109.48,"stop":1111.749,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"What's important?","start":1111.749,"stop":1112.366,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"--What is important here is that the premise of the Ninth Circuit's opinion is that it would be an acceptable motion for substitution for the -- for Mr. Clair to complain or allege disagreements with his counsel about--","start":1112.366,"stop":1127.109,"duration":14.74}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"All right, so what's bothering you is the way they applied it.","start":1127.109,"stop":1130.228,"duration":3.12}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well--","start":1130.228,"stop":1131.128,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"And they applied it in circumstances that you think -- the district judge actually, his decision was fine.","start":1131.128,"stop":1138.065,"duration":6.94},{"text":"You don't have the power to set that aside because it was within -- it's within the scope of any kind of standard you want to call it, including calling it \"interest of justice\".","start":1138.065,"stop":1149.539,"duration":11.47},{"text":"Am I right in thinking that, that that's really your concern?","start":1149.539,"stop":1153.159,"duration":3.62}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes, our concern, Your Honor, is that the premise of the Ninth Circuit's opinion is -- goes to what the appropriate standard, what the appropriate level of complaint, whatever you want to call it--","start":1153.159,"stop":1166.501,"duration":13.34}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"So what you really want us to do is to look at the record of the case, go through it, and say, here, whatever words you want to use, the district court acted in his discretion in saying don't change the counsel?","start":1166.501,"stop":1179.561,"duration":13.06},{"text":"Is that what I'm supposed to do?","start":1179.561,"stop":1182.227,"duration":2.67},{"text":"I'm trying to get at what you want me to do.","start":1182.227,"stop":1183.696,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes, that is -- yes.","start":1183.696,"stop":1184.846,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, no, you don't want that.","start":1184.846,"stop":1186.065,"duration":1.22},{"text":"You don't want to stay whatever words you used.","start":1186.065,"stop":1188.916,"duration":2.85}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"No--","start":1188.916,"stop":1189.549,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"You want us to say the words to be used are the words that we use in deciding whether you have been accorded your constitutional right to counsel, right?","start":1189.549,"stop":1200.724,"duration":11.17}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"That's -- that's correct, Your Honor.","start":1200.724,"stop":1203.759,"duration":3.04},{"text":"I think the confusion here--","start":1203.759,"stop":1204.909,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"--I didn't mean literally \"whatever words you use\".","start":1204.909,"stop":1207.728,"duration":2.82},{"text":"I'm trying to figure out what you want me to do.","start":1207.728,"stop":1209.846,"duration":2.12},{"text":"One is to go back and search all the cases that use some words for a standard, which, as you can tell, I'm reluctant to think that that is meaningful in this case.","start":1209.846,"stop":1217.35,"duration":7.5},{"text":"The other is to look at the record to see if he acted within what you would normally think of as the district court's discretionary authority.","start":1217.35,"stop":1225.706,"duration":8.36}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"--I think the confusion here is caused by the fact that the Ninth Circuit opinion started out by borrowing the phrase \"interest of justice\" and inserting it into a section where -- where it was not inserted, and it would appear to be a deliberate act of Congress to do that, and then it gave it a meaning which we think under any circumstances would be inappropriate in this context.","start":1225.706,"stop":1250.573,"duration":24.87}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose you don't think that the standard of review is abuse of discretion, because if you do then I suppose you are assuming that the district court has discretion whether to grant the motion or not instead of being confined by a particular standard.","start":1250.573,"stop":1267.2,"duration":16.63}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, abuse of discretion -- if the Court is wrong as a matter of law, of course, it automatically -- I mean, that is an abuse of discretion.","start":1267.2,"stop":1274.355,"duration":7.15},{"text":"And our feeling here about the Ninth Circuit's opinion is that the way it has defined what would be appropriate in terms of a motion for a substitution and what would trigger an inquiry by the judge, as a matter of law the Ninth Circuit was wrong in this case.","start":1274.355,"stop":1291.748,"duration":17.39}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but abuse of discretion doesn't mean that the judge operates in a vacuum.","start":1291.748,"stop":1296.202,"duration":4.45},{"text":"If we make -- issue an opinion and say, oh, well, the standard is an abuse of discretion, that doesn't tell people too much.","start":1296.202,"stop":1305.075,"duration":8.87},{"text":"Abuse of discretion based on what standards, what inquiries?","start":1305.075,"stop":1308.76,"duration":3.68},{"text":"And that's -- I would like to know what your position is on that, because it seems to me that at the end of the day it's going to be something very close to interest of justice.","start":1308.76,"stop":1319.484,"duration":10.72}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, the substance -- if we want to call it an interest of justice standard, the substance of it would be that it would not be -- substitution would not be -- it would not be appropriate to move for substitution on the basis of disagreements with counsel about tactical or investigative decisions, such as Mr. Clair did here.","start":1319.484,"stop":1344.283,"duration":24.8},{"text":"The appropriate standard is whether or not there has been an actual denial of counsel as provided under section 3599.","start":1344.283,"stop":1351.271,"duration":6.99}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Counsel, could I give you an example?","start":1351.271,"stop":1352.655,"duration":1.38},{"text":"Beginning of the litigation, all right?","start":1352.655,"stop":1356.257,"duration":3.6},{"text":"Capital counsel is appointed.","start":1356.257,"stop":1358.875,"duration":2.62},{"text":"Capital counsel wants to raise challenges to the conviction and sentence, and defendant says: I don't -- I want to die.","start":1358.875,"stop":1367.229,"duration":8.35},{"text":"Is the district court entitled to substitute that counsel under your theory?","start":1367.229,"stop":1376.001,"duration":8.77},{"text":"Because you said to me it has to be counsel that's -- that counsel that has abandoned the client.","start":1376.001,"stop":1382.238,"duration":6.24},{"text":"Counsel doesn't want to abandon the client, counsel wants to prosecute the case.","start":1382.238,"stop":1385.792,"duration":3.55},{"text":"There is no conflict of interest.","start":1385.792,"stop":1387.858,"duration":2.07},{"text":"Counsel's not representing anybody else.","start":1387.858,"stop":1389.927,"duration":2.07},{"text":"And what was your third criteria?","start":1389.927,"stop":1392.529,"duration":2.6}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"Qualifications, just the basic--","start":1392.529,"stop":1395.048,"duration":2.52}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, this is Seth Waxman, sitting right next to you.","start":1395.048,"stop":1399.783,"duration":4.73}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"--He's undoubtedly qualified, Your Honor.","start":1399.783,"stop":1401.635,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"I suspect that's the case.","start":1401.635,"stop":1403.987,"duration":2.35}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"Otherwise he wouldn't have the appointment.","start":1403.987,"stop":1405.67,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"So beginning of the case, first decision, and defendant comes in and says: Substitute my attorney.","start":1405.67,"stop":1414.71,"duration":9.04},{"text":"What would be your argument under your test?","start":1414.71,"stop":1418.263,"duration":3.55}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"There are several responses to that.","start":1418.263,"stop":1421.198,"duration":2.94},{"text":"At one level the client would always -- always has and I think always has basic decisionmaking authority over basic decisions, whether or not a petition should be filed or not filed, this type of thing.","start":1421.198,"stop":1436.308,"duration":15.11},{"text":"So a failure of an attorney to abide by that particular instruction would in fact be a failure--","start":1436.308,"stop":1443.062,"duration":6.75}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"So there are some decisions that the client controls?","start":1443.062,"stop":1446.764,"duration":3.7}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"--There have always been some basic decisions the client makes in any, in any case.","start":1446.764,"stop":1451.482,"duration":4.72},{"text":"But it's not--","start":1451.482,"stop":1452.199,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"But that's not abandonment.","start":1452.199,"stop":1454.784,"duration":2.59},{"text":"That's an error.","start":1454.784,"stop":1456.303,"duration":1.52},{"text":"That's a problem.","start":1456.303,"stop":1459.588,"duration":3.28},{"text":"But it's not abandonment under your definition.","start":1459.588,"stop":1462.79,"duration":3.2}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"--It is in fact the failure of the lawyer to truly act as an agent for the client at that point.","start":1462.79,"stop":1472.329,"duration":9.54}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if I tell my attorney, follow these leads, that's a failure of an agent as well.","start":1472.329,"stop":1479.235,"duration":6.91}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"It's actually, though -- that is in fact normally always considered to be an area that's within the domain of the attorney.","start":1479.235,"stop":1487.839,"duration":8.6},{"text":"Those types of investigative tactical decisions have always been decisions that attorneys have normally made for their clients and not necessarily under the control of their clients.","start":1487.839,"stop":1497.03,"duration":9.19},{"text":"But let me tell you about the volunteer situation, as a practical matter.","start":1497.03,"stop":1501.599,"duration":4.57},{"text":"The volunteer situation is a whole -- almost a whole separate category of litigation from the kind of litigation we are talking about.","start":1501.599,"stop":1509.354,"duration":7.76},{"text":"What normally happens in those cases is counsel is not substituted; usually frequently a second counsel is brought in to deal with representing the client on those particular issues, and the first counsel remains.","start":1509.354,"stop":1524.014,"duration":14.66},{"text":"So that's become--","start":1524.014,"stop":1525.364,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Volunteer issue?","start":1525.364,"stop":1526.882,"duration":1.52},{"text":"What are you talking about?","start":1526.882,"stop":1527.682,"duration":0.8},{"text":"I'm--","start":1527.682,"stop":1528.332,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"--A volunteer issue is when someone says: I do not want to pursue my remedies, I want to simply be executed.","start":1528.332,"stop":1533.886,"duration":5.55},{"text":"In the practice we call that a volunteer.","start":1533.886,"stop":1536.672,"duration":2.79}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--You call that a volunteer--","start":1536.672,"stop":1537.238,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"We call that a volunteer.","start":1537.238,"stop":1537.805,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--Volunteer.","start":1537.805,"stop":1538.274,"duration":0.47},{"text":"Volunteering to be executed?","start":1538.274,"stop":1540.14,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the normal term of art.","start":1540.14,"stop":1542.659,"duration":2.52}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Given my example, isn't it the case that under the interest of justice standard there will be situations in which a substitution like the one I just posited would be right, that wouldn't be right under your standard?","start":1542.659,"stop":1558.768,"duration":16.11}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I think that actually our standard would cover what is appropriate for protecting the defendant's statutory right to counsel, and that--","start":1558.768,"stop":1570.759,"duration":11.99}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you suggesting that for noncapital defendants Congress chose to give them more rather than less?","start":1570.759,"stop":1576.98,"duration":6.22}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"--No, not at all.","start":1576.98,"stop":1578.432,"duration":1.45},{"text":"I don't think noncapital or capital habeas petitioners have any greater, have any greater right to the assistance of counsel.","start":1578.432,"stop":1586.938,"duration":8.51}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"But you are saying capital have lesser rights.","start":1586.938,"stop":1588.371,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"My guess -- I don't think this Court has ever drawn a categorical difference between them in terms of what rights are available to them for purposes of representation by counsel.","start":1588.371,"stop":1597.326,"duration":8.95}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't delay one of the factors that courts routinely look at under the interest of justice standard?","start":1597.326,"stop":1603.997,"duration":6.67}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1603.997,"stop":1604.649,"duration":0.65},{"text":"And I -- Once again, any motion for substitution, no matter what standard you use, should be made promptly.","start":1604.649,"stop":1612.069,"duration":7.42}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"So we go back to Justice Breyer's point that, even under the interest of justice standard, you are claiming there was an error?","start":1612.069,"stop":1618.573,"duration":6.5}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"Absolutely.","start":1618.573,"stop":1619.909,"duration":1.34},{"text":"Oh, yes.","start":1619.909,"stop":1620.375,"duration":0.47},{"text":"Yes.","start":1620.375,"stop":1620.942,"duration":0.57},{"text":"We would submit even under that standard it would be an error.","start":1620.942,"stop":1624.294,"duration":3.35},{"text":"Your Honor, unless there is any more questions--","start":1624.294,"stop":1627.179,"duration":2.88}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel.","start":1627.179,"stop":1628.013,"duration":0.83},{"text":"Mr. Waxman.","start":1628.013,"stop":1633.232,"duration":5.22}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:","start":1633.232,"stop":1635.934,"duration":2.7},{"text":"The court of appeals held that it was an abuse of discretion to deny substitution without making any inquiry, even of counsel, into the specific situation alleged by Mr. Clair.","start":1635.934,"stop":1650.211,"duration":14.28},{"text":"The Court did not hold that Mr. Clair was entitled to substitute counsel.","start":1650.211,"stop":1655.332,"duration":5.12},{"text":"It did not hold that he was entitled to amend his petition.","start":1655.332,"stop":1660.567,"duration":5.23},{"text":"It did not hold that substitute counsel was even required or advised to seek--","start":1660.567,"stop":1666.154,"duration":5.59}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't he always--","start":1666.154,"stop":1667.073,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So what if last week we get notice from Mr. Clair that he is dissatisfied with his Supreme Court counsel; that communication has broken down; that you plan to argue particular -- present particular arguments, and he doesn't want you to do that.","start":1667.073,"stop":1684.851,"duration":17.78},{"text":"Do we have an obligation to conduct an inquiry into his complaint?","start":1684.851,"stop":1689.753,"duration":4.9}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"--I think if you have any obligation whatsoever -- and I want to make clear that there are -- these kinds of letters and requests for last minute substitutions happen all the time and in the mine run there may not be any duty of independent inquiry.","start":1689.753,"stop":1704.779,"duration":15.03},{"text":"If you had one, it would simply be to do what the Court did in March, which is to inquire of the two counsel in the case, is there anything to this, and then rule.","start":1704.779,"stop":1715.32,"duration":10.54}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1715.32,"stop":1715.803,"duration":0.48},{"text":"He says, I turned up new evidence, or I think this is a great argument, and my counsel has told me he is not going to raise it, and I want new counsel who will raise this argument.","start":1715.803,"stop":1728.544,"duration":12.74},{"text":"Will we have to say -- look at it and say, well, we have to figure out is that a good argument; is it better than the ones counsel are going to raise?","start":1728.544,"stop":1736.217,"duration":7.67},{"text":"Has communication broken down?","start":1736.217,"stop":1737.819,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"No, of course not.","start":1737.819,"stop":1739.419,"duration":1.6},{"text":"In this situation, the Court had pending before it a first petition for habeas corpus that alleged both ineffective assistance of counsel at trial and specific Brady violations.","start":1739.419,"stop":1752.845,"duration":13.43},{"text":"And by the way, in answer to your first question, the district judge announced that he was retiring on June 27th, effective the 30th.","start":1752.845,"stop":1762.717,"duration":9.87},{"text":"So this was beforehand.","start":1762.717,"stop":1763.751,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I want to ask you about that.","start":1763.751,"stop":1764.819,"duration":1.07},{"text":"You mention that no fewer than six times in your brief.","start":1764.819,"stop":1767.671,"duration":2.85},{"text":"What is your point, that the judge altered his disposition of a legal matter before him for his personal convenience?","start":1767.671,"stop":1774.859,"duration":7.19}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1774.859,"stop":1775.375,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Then what is the significance of the fact that he was going to retire?","start":1775.375,"stop":1778.813,"duration":3.44}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- the significance of the fact that he -- he hadn't announced that he was going to retire.","start":1778.813,"stop":1786.5,"duration":7.69},{"text":"The significance of the fact that he did retire is only to my mind an explanation for why he failed to conduct the minimal inquiry--","start":1786.5,"stop":1796.188,"duration":9.69}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So you are saying--","start":1796.188,"stop":1796.857,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"--that he had previously--","start":1796.857,"stop":1797.874,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--So you are saying he violated his judicial oath for his own personal convenience, that he failed to do something that you say he should have done, because he was retiring?","start":1797.874,"stop":1806.313,"duration":8.44}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"--I'm not -- he -- The error would have been the same if he had stayed on the bench for another 10 years.","start":1806.313,"stop":1813.067,"duration":6.75}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So why do you say six times in your brief that the judge was retiring the next day or retired the next day?","start":1813.067,"stop":1817.938,"duration":4.87}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"Because -- It goes to their complaints with the remedy in the case.","start":1817.938,"stop":1821.656,"duration":3.72},{"text":"That is, they are faulting that the remedy is not: Go back and ask this judge to decide whether substitution was appropriate.","start":1821.656,"stop":1828.594,"duration":6.94}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"There's another judge.","start":1828.594,"stop":1829.162,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1829.162,"stop":1829.779,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"There's another judge.","start":1829.779,"stop":1830.662,"duration":0.88},{"text":"She's available.","start":1830.662,"stop":1831.279,"duration":0.62},{"text":"I have to say it strikes me, frankly, as argument by innuendo that I think is very unjustified.","start":1831.279,"stop":1835.832,"duration":4.55}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I apologize if it gave that impression.","start":1835.832,"stop":1838.534,"duration":2.7},{"text":"I don't mean any innuendo in the case.","start":1838.534,"stop":1841.219,"duration":2.68},{"text":"Our proposition is simply this: Prior to adjudicating the claims of ineffective assistance of counsel and Brady, when the court receives a letter that says, Your Honor, I'm sorry for writing a second time.","start":1841.219,"stop":1857.579,"duration":16.36},{"text":"As you know, I have always maintained that I'm innocent.","start":1857.579,"stop":1861.398,"duration":3.82},{"text":"My investigator has just discovered physical evidence in of the State's files that he believes may clear me.","start":1861.398,"stop":1870.406,"duration":9.01},{"text":"My counsel--","start":1870.406,"stop":1870.906,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"--Mr. Waxman, what--","start":1870.906,"stop":1871.356,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm still trying to get to the point -- I'm sorry.","start":1871.356,"stop":1873.441,"duration":2.09},{"text":"I'm still trying to get to the point of the relevance of the fact that he was retiring.","start":1873.441,"stop":1876.993,"duration":3.55}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"--It goes to the remedy, and it goes to the fact he--","start":1876.993,"stop":1881.812,"duration":4.82}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"How does it go -- How does it go to the remedy?","start":1881.812,"stop":1884.147,"duration":2.34}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"--It -- they are alleging that there was an abuse of discretion not to send it back to the judge to do what he had declined to do.","start":1884.147,"stop":1892.002,"duration":7.86},{"text":"And our proposition is, because substitute counsel had been in place for 5 years and because the judge who had superintended the case for 12 years was no longer there, it was appropriate and within the court of appeals' discretion under 28 U.S.C. 2106 to remand it to the new judge, with new counsel, for -- to allow new counsel simply to ask the new judge, who had not heard all of the witnesses or the evidence, to demonstrate why, if counsel thought it was appropriate, to allow him to amend the petition under Rule 15(a)(2).","start":1892.002,"stop":1930.211,"duration":38.21}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that was the--","start":1930.211,"stop":1930.544,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"--Mr. Waxman--","start":1930.544,"stop":1930.827,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That would be pretty incredible.","start":1930.827,"stop":1931.727,"duration":0.9},{"text":"Maybe that's what's required.","start":1931.727,"stop":1935.029,"duration":3.3},{"text":"Why isn't this is a fair reading of what Judge Taylor did?","start":1935.029,"stop":1939.667,"duration":4.64},{"text":"As of April 29th, as I recall, there was not a problem with the representation.","start":1939.667,"stop":1947.337,"duration":7.67},{"text":"And the decision was made on June 30th.","start":1947.337,"stop":1950.639,"duration":3.3},{"text":"Now, on June 16th, that's the time when Clair sent his letter.","start":1950.639,"stop":1955.592,"duration":4.95},{"text":"By this point, the petition had been pending for a long time before the judge.","start":1955.592,"stop":1960.413,"duration":4.82},{"text":"The judge presumably was approaching the point where he was going to issue his decision.","start":1960.413,"stop":1966.567,"duration":6.15},{"text":"He saw the letter.","start":1966.567,"stop":1969.169,"duration":2.6},{"text":"He could not see any way in which the matters that were discussed in the letters could lead to a claim that would go anywhere.","start":1969.169,"stop":1979.308,"duration":10.14},{"text":"As to the physical evidence, if it couldn't have been tested at the time of trial, there would not have been a Brady obligation, and an actual innocence claim here would be quite far-fetched in light of the very incriminating statements that -- that Mr. Clair made in the tape recorded conversation.","start":1979.308,"stop":2000.305,"duration":21},{"text":"Had he substituted counsel, he would not have been under an obligation, I think, to allow substituted counsel to amend the petition, which had been pending for a long period of time.","start":2000.305,"stop":2010.413,"duration":10.11},{"text":"So he said: Counsel is doing a proper job; there doesn't appear to be a conflict of interest; and I'm going to deny this.","start":2010.413,"stop":2018.6,"duration":8.19},{"text":"Now, counsel could have been appointed and in fact was appointed to represent Mr. Clair going forward.","start":2018.6,"stop":2023.154,"duration":4.55},{"text":"Why isn't that a fair reading of what he did?","start":2023.154,"stop":2025.606,"duration":2.45},{"text":"And if so, what need was there for further inquiry?","start":2025.606,"stop":2028.475,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, this -- it may very well be what was in his thought processes, but we don't know that.","start":2028.475,"stop":2034.644,"duration":6.17}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"But we know what was in his thought processes, Mr. Waxman, because 14 days later he issued a 60 or 61-page opinion with -- dealing with 47 different claims, many of which, many of which, related to actual innocence, which was the gravamen of the letter of the complaint on the 16th.","start":2034.644,"stop":2054.722,"duration":20.08},{"text":"So you -- you can't consider the letter just in isolation from the 61-page opinion that's issued 16 days later.","start":2054.722,"stop":2062.312,"duration":7.59}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I -- I think that the -- that a district judge faced with a request to substitute counsel at this very late stage is appropriately -- appropriately takes into account everything that has happened, everything that he has allowed to happen, everything that defense counsel has -- has done, and he is obviously permitted to approach this request with a high degree of skepticism, and a strong--","start":2062.312,"stop":2086.26,"duration":23.95}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"--And you are suggesting, Mr. Waxman, that he did not have to make an inquiry in every case, is that right?","start":2086.26,"stop":2091.314,"duration":5.05},{"text":"You are not saying that.","start":2091.314,"stop":2092.064,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"--That's right.","start":2092.064,"stop":2092.714,"duration":0.65},{"text":"I mean--","start":2092.714,"stop":2093.314,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"So what -- when does a person have to make an inquiry?","start":2093.314,"stop":2097.051,"duration":3.74}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, of course--","start":2097.051,"stop":2098.518,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"What in this case required an inquiry on the judge's part?","start":2098.518,"stop":2102.872,"duration":4.35}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"--I think, you know, if the district judge is presented with factually supported allegations that appointed counsel has failed to pursue newly discovered evidence that may be germane to an issue to be decided, especially where the potential import of that evidence is specifically explicated and corroborated by a willing percipient witness, in this case the investigator who viewed it, the district judge has an obligation simply to ask counsel for the State and counsel for the defense, please respond, as the judge did in June -- in March.","start":2102.872,"stop":2145.482,"duration":42.61},{"text":"Now, in March the judge -- the judge asked for a response--","start":2145.482,"stop":2149.518,"duration":4.04}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I guess this goes back to Justice Alito's question, but suppose the judge says to himself, even if the response comes in, yes, relations are terrible because the client wants the lawyers to -- to investigate a particular thing and the lawyers don't want to investigate that thing, the judge knows, it doesn't make a difference either way, because he is ready to issue his opinion.","start":2149.518,"stop":2173.485,"duration":23.97},{"text":"And further investigation of this evidence is not going to change his mind as to any material issue.","start":2173.485,"stop":2179.455,"duration":5.97},{"text":"Why should the judge not reject the motion?","start":2179.455,"stop":2182.139,"duration":2.68}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, because the judge could not know that based on the allegations in the Ford letter and the Clair letter.","start":2182.139,"stop":2189.411,"duration":7.27},{"text":"It is not the case, going to Justice Alito's point from my question to my friend, that what was represented in that letter, the new physical evidence related only to DNA testing.","start":2189.411,"stop":2201.902,"duration":12.49},{"text":"There was a specific allegation that there were fingerprints located at the scene of the crime that previously had been represented to the trial court and to defense counsel either to be unusable or on materials that had gone through the U.S. mail so that the probative value would be limited, and both of those things were untrue.","start":2201.902,"stop":2223.066,"duration":21.16},{"text":"And Mr. Ford said to the judge:","start":2223.066,"stop":2225.084,"duration":2.02},{"text":"\"I'm prepared to explain to you exactly what those prints are, and they have not been tested against anyone, including the other people who were suspected of the identical type murder the night before in the same area or other potential suspects in this case like Mr. Henrickson. \"","start":2225.084,"stop":2245.664,"duration":20.58}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"The Ninth Circuit -- I see -- I think I see what they were trying to get at.","start":2245.664,"stop":2252.001,"duration":6.34},{"text":"They want -- they don't see anything practical here to do except to try to get the judge, the district judge, to focus on the question of whether the petition should be amended to assert this kind of claim about the new physical evidence; is that right?","start":2252.001,"stop":2266.495,"duration":14.49}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2266.495,"stop":2267.111,"duration":0.62},{"text":"They were--","start":2267.111,"stop":2267.545,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"That's where they were trying to go.","start":2267.545,"stop":2268.28,"duration":0.74},{"text":"Okay.","start":2268.28,"stop":2268.68,"duration":0.4},{"text":"Now, suppose you lose this case.","start":2268.68,"stop":2270.447,"duration":1.77},{"text":"Suppose they were to say -- suppose this Court said, well, to tell you the truth, that district judge was operating within his authority in saying that this counsel can continue to represent him.","start":2270.447,"stop":2287.241,"duration":16.79},{"text":"We know subsequently relations broke down and now there is a new counsel.","start":2287.241,"stop":2291.795,"duration":4.55},{"text":"All right?","start":2291.795,"stop":2292.778,"duration":0.98},{"text":"Can't the new counsel go back to the district court and say, judge, we would like to amend the petition so that you will consider, you know, whether it should be amended to include this physical evidence claim?","start":2292.778,"stop":2304.886,"duration":12.11},{"text":"Couldn't he do that?","start":2304.886,"stop":2305.57,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"--He can't ask to amend a petition in a case in which there's a final judgment.","start":2305.57,"stop":2310.44,"duration":4.87},{"text":"He could file a -- he could file a Rule 60(b) motion, which he did in this case.","start":2310.44,"stop":2315.994,"duration":5.55}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"And what did--","start":2315.994,"stop":2316.644,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"And very--","start":2316.644,"stop":2317.278,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"--I think you answered this, but I can't remember the answer.","start":2317.278,"stop":2320.981,"duration":3.7},{"text":"What happened when he filed the 60(b)?","start":2320.981,"stop":2322.997,"duration":2.02},{"text":"Did they amend the petition or did they consider the thing or not?","start":2322.997,"stop":2325.883,"duration":2.89}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"--No.","start":2325.883,"stop":2326.349,"duration":0.47},{"text":"While the appeal was pending, so that he wouldn't be accused of having simply sat on his rights while the Ninth Circuit was deciding, he filed a Rule 60 -- he filed for leave to file a Rule 60(b) motion and said in essence: Look, the investigator has discovered this new evidence; I haven't been able to test it or examine it; please give me leave to do that, because I believe it may support reopening the judgment.","start":2326.349,"stop":2351.934,"duration":25.59},{"text":"The district judge said: I'm not going to allow you to make that motion.","start":2351.934,"stop":2355.819,"duration":3.88},{"text":"The Ninth Circuit issued a mandamus directing the district judge to rule on the motion.","start":2355.819,"stop":2361.039,"duration":5.22},{"text":"She then denied it, essentially finding that the motion should be denied because Mr. Grele, substitute counsel, hadn't already proven to her what it is that he was seeking to find out, that is what does this evidence show.","start":2361.039,"stop":2380.02,"duration":18.98}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"So there is no -- so in other words -- what the Ninth Circuit in my view is trying to do is they've worked out some complicated way of trying to get the district court to consider the motion about the new physical evidence.","start":2380.02,"stop":2392.244,"duration":12.22},{"text":"And if that's right, then unless you -- there is no way to get there.","start":2392.244,"stop":2399.432,"duration":7.19},{"text":"I don't see how you get there under the law.","start":2399.432,"stop":2401.449,"duration":2.02},{"text":"That's my -- but--","start":2401.449,"stop":2403.233,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Mister--","start":2403.233,"stop":2403.801,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"--I'd just like to know what he's thinking.","start":2403.801,"stop":2406.251,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"I have an answer to your question, but of course I'll defer to any superseding question from--","start":2406.251,"stop":2410.805,"duration":4.55}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"--It has to go with the scope of the remedy that they did.","start":2410.805,"stop":2413.924,"duration":3.12}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"--Uh-huh.","start":2413.924,"stop":2414.424,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Assuming, as I do and you just said, that what the Ninth Circuit said is there is -- he should have gotten a reason, an explanation, but now there is a new attorney anyway, so what do we do, isn't the normal thing to do just to remand it, to let the district court decide what steps it wants to take, including to decide whether or not it would have granted the motion for substitution if it had heard the explanation?","start":2414.424,"stop":2442.843,"duration":28.42}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2442.843,"stop":2444.776,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Meaning, there was a new judge.","start":2444.776,"stop":2447.662,"duration":2.89},{"text":"But, that doesn't -- a new judge is never stopped from considering what has happened in the case.","start":2447.662,"stop":2453.314,"duration":5.65}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2453.314,"stop":2453.649,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"And to decide whether under the facts as they existed at the time.","start":2453.649,"stop":2457.451,"duration":3.8}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course not.","start":2457.451,"stop":2459.47,"duration":2.02},{"text":"I mean, even the State acknowledges that asking the judge whether or not there should be substitution when there has been substituted counsel since the appeal was taken is, as they call it, an academic exercise.","start":2459.47,"stop":2473.377,"duration":13.91},{"text":"But technically the judge--","start":2473.377,"stop":2474.393,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"But it's not academic.","start":2474.393,"stop":2474.96,"duration":0.57},{"text":"It wasn't academic for the judge below, the new judge--","start":2474.96,"stop":2478.029,"duration":3.07}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well--","start":2478.029,"stop":2478.695,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"--to say, what happened back then; I don't believe the motion was timely; I don't believe that you were foreclosed from doing other things; motion to substitute would have been denied; end of case.","start":2478.695,"stop":2494.957,"duration":16.26}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"--I guess I'm not sure there is a huge difference between that and what the Ninth Circuit did or what I understand the Ninth Circuit to be doing, which was to issue an order -- basically say the substitution motion had to be decided within the broad discretion that the law allows before entry of judgment.","start":2494.957,"stop":2514.784,"duration":19.83},{"text":"I'm going -- we are going to do as best we can to put Mr. Clair back in that position.","start":2514.784,"stop":2521.038,"duration":6.25},{"text":"It seems to us that since he -- since counsel said, represented, as soon as it was asked after his letter, there is an irreconcilable breakdown and substitution is advised--","start":2521.038,"stop":2534.098,"duration":13.06}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Counsel--","start":2534.098,"stop":2534.665,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"--he has counsel and -- I'm sorry.","start":2534.665,"stop":2536.55,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--No.","start":2536.55,"stop":2536.95,"duration":0.4},{"text":"I'm trying to help you.","start":2536.95,"stop":2538.117,"duration":1.17},{"text":"I understood you to say you had an answer to Justice Breyer's question?","start":2538.117,"stop":2541.769,"duration":3.65}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I do have an answer to Justice Breyer's question, if I can just -- thank you.","start":2541.769,"stop":2546.323,"duration":4.55},{"text":"If I can just finish answering -- I apologize for my lengthy answers.","start":2546.323,"stop":2551.044,"duration":4.72}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Why don't you finish your answer to Justice Sotomayor and then go back to Justice Breyer.","start":2551.044,"stop":2555.261,"duration":4.22}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":2555.261,"stop":2555.645,"duration":0.38},{"text":"In essence what has happened, what I understand the court of appeals to have decided is to say: Look, because we have had substitute counsel for 5 years and the FPD has said it couldn't continue, we're allowing this to go back and let substitute counsel convince the judge, if it can, if it chooses to, whether or not to exercise its considerable discretion in allowing leave to amend the petition before judgment.","start":2555.645,"stop":2585.798,"duration":30.15},{"text":"The judge may very well say no, and the case is then back before us.","start":2585.798,"stop":2589.835,"duration":4.04},{"text":"But it might say yes.","start":2589.835,"stop":2591.269,"duration":1.43},{"text":"In other words, to do what in essence is the prejudice or materiality inquiry that Judge Taylor would have engaged in if he found that there was a breakdown.","start":2591.269,"stop":2601.809,"duration":10.54},{"text":"If mean, if there's a breakdown and the judge says that the only new evidence is that the moon was in the fifth house and that doesn't depend on anything, I'm denying -- or it was a new moon, I'm denying this.","start":2601.809,"stop":2614.384,"duration":12.57},{"text":"Justice Breyer, I -- I agree with you that the Ninth Circuit was struggling to figure out a way to most efficiently resolve the multiple appeals that were pending in front of them.","start":2614.384,"stop":2629.227,"duration":14.84},{"text":"And they understood from the Rule 60(b) appeal that was also pending and from the appeal on the denial of substitution that there was this newly discovered evidence in the State's files; that the investigator who looked at it thought that it was really important; and they had no record about what it was or whether it should have been considered.","start":2629.227,"stop":2653.192,"duration":23.97},{"text":"Now, they could have said, well, we're going to direct the Rule 60(b) judge to grant leave to examine the physical evidence and analyze it.","start":2653.192,"stop":2664.317,"duration":11.13},{"text":"And it was an abuse of discretion of the Rule 60(b) judge not to allow Mr. Clair at least to make some showing.","start":2664.317,"stop":2672.423,"duration":8.11},{"text":"But the more straightforward way would have been to say: You didn't inquire of counsel; counsel may have had a very good reason for not pursuing this; but in the face of the specific allegation by a willing, percipient witness that there is highly material evidence in the State files and the public defender is refusing to do anything about it, all we think the Ninth Circuit was holding is--","start":2672.423,"stop":2700.073,"duration":27.65}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"That's like -- Mr. Waxman--","start":2700.073,"stop":2701.173,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"--it was an abuse of discretion not to ask.","start":2701.173,"stop":2702.473,"duration":1.3},{"text":"I'm sorry, Justice Ginsburg.","start":2702.473,"stop":2703.358,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"--Mr. Waxman, I thought this is a case that has been going on for, like, 12 years in the district court.","start":2703.358,"stop":2706.827,"duration":3.47}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2706.827,"stop":2707.293,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"And I thought that the basic disagreement between the client and counsel was counsel said: Our best shot is going to be to keep you alive, so we want to do everything we can to change the death sentence, and then -- and we don't want to detract from that by making a claim of actual innocence when the -- there'd be very slim basis for that.","start":2707.293,"stop":2738.112,"duration":30.82},{"text":"So, that's the judgment, and it's a strategic judgment, that counsel made: Our best shot to keep this man alive is to concentrate on the penalty phase.","start":2738.112,"stop":2750.689,"duration":12.58}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"Justice Ginsburg, if that had -- if the judge had inquired of counsel and counsel had given that reason, that would be something that the Court could evaluate in deciding whether the balancing test that is required by the interests of justice standard satisfied his inquiry.","start":2750.689,"stop":2770.667,"duration":19.98},{"text":"But we don't have any -- I doubt very much that that is what counsel would have said.","start":2770.667,"stop":2774.887,"duration":4.22}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Counsel, if -- the interests of justice, does that include the available resources of the Federal Public Defender?","start":2774.887,"stop":2782.225,"duration":7.34},{"text":"I mean, those offices are notoriously understaffed.","start":2782.225,"stop":2786.362,"duration":4.14},{"text":"And here you have a situation where one lawyer has been representing an individual for an awful long time, and the defendant says, I want a new lawyer.","start":2786.362,"stop":2794.199,"duration":7.84},{"text":"It's obviously going to take that -- a new lawyer away from their work and put them in a position of having to get up to speed in a new case.","start":2794.199,"stop":2801.788,"duration":7.59},{"text":"And I just wonder if that's part of this -- I won't call interest of justice","start":2801.788,"stop":2807.692,"duration":5.9},{"text":"\"a standard -- it's an aspiration. \"","start":2807.692,"stop":2809.96,"duration":2.27},{"text":"\"But does that go into the calculus? \"","start":2809.96,"stop":2813.179,"duration":3.22}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"I would think that that -- not only that goes into the calculus, but all of the I would say well-articulated doctrines that Congress and this Court have applied essentially establishing presumptions against reopening long-litigated matters, whether--","start":2813.179,"stop":2834.36,"duration":21.18}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that gets to my--","start":2834.36,"stop":2835.293,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"--All of those things go into the interest of justice balancing.","start":2835.293,"stop":2837.562,"duration":2.27},{"text":"There's no doubt about it.","start":2837.562,"stop":2838.762,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Is the -- is the person in a different position with the new counsel than he would have been with the old concerning the standards about reopening things?","start":2838.762,"stop":2848.451,"duration":9.69},{"text":"In other words, do we say, well, what would the old counsel have been able to do with respect to reopening, and say, well, that's all the new counsel can do?","start":2848.451,"stop":2857.306,"duration":8.86},{"text":"In other words, new counsel doesn't allow you to circumvent the various--","start":2857.306,"stop":2860.425,"duration":3.12}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course.","start":2860.425,"stop":2860.808,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--the restrictions that you just talked about.","start":2860.808,"stop":2862.027,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course -- of course not.","start":2862.027,"stop":2863.043,"duration":1.02},{"text":"The only point is, what -- what Clair was basically saying is, my investigator has just found evidence that he believes is highly exculpatory, physical evidence in the State's files that was previously represented not to exist.","start":2863.043,"stop":2878.137,"duration":15.09},{"text":"My counsel is refusing to do anything about it.","start":2878.137,"stop":2881.841,"duration":3.7},{"text":"Please give me somebody, whether it's -- have my counsel do it or some new counsel, to present this to the judge, just so the judge can decide in evaluating these, the Brady and the ineffective assistance claim.","start":2881.841,"stop":2895.099,"duration":13.26},{"text":"And if this is as represented, it could be highly material to those claims.","start":2895.099,"stop":2899.067,"duration":3.97}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And one of the things I think the district court would do in that situation with the same counsel is say: Look, this was a tactical strategic decision of the lawyer.","start":2899.067,"stop":2907.572,"duration":8.51},{"text":"You don't get to reopen something because of that.","start":2907.572,"stop":2910.091,"duration":2.52},{"text":"Now, does that same consideration apply with respect to the substituted counsel, or does the substituted counsel allow the defendant to get a leg up on the process, and make new arguments that the old counsel couldn't make?","start":2910.091,"stop":2923.918,"duration":13.83}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think that in a value -- if substitute counsel -- if there is a remand in this case and substitute counsel makes a Rule 15 motion, the Court will evaluate that under the broad interests of justice standard.","start":2923.918,"stop":2938.444,"duration":14.53},{"text":"I mean, whoever the counsel is has to acquit his or her professional obligations.","start":2938.444,"stop":2943.58,"duration":5.14},{"text":"It may very well have been, Mr. Chief Justice, that if Judge Taylor had said, look, I -- please write to me in 3 days or let's have a status conference and explain to me what's going on; I understand you went to see this evidence.","start":2943.58,"stop":2958.172,"duration":14.59},{"text":"Why aren't you -- is it true that you are not pursuing it?","start":2958.172,"stop":2960.791,"duration":2.62},{"text":"And if so, why not?","start":2960.791,"stop":2961.976,"duration":1.18},{"text":"That would have completely acquitted the judge's responsibility.","start":2961.976,"stop":2965.928,"duration":3.95}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Waxman, the State contends that the interests of justice standard is not the right one.","start":2965.928,"stop":2972.082,"duration":6.15},{"text":"Why do you contend that it is?","start":2972.082,"stop":2975.367,"duration":3.29},{"text":"It doesn't appear in -- in 3599, even though it did appear in -- in the previous provision that used to cover these cases, which is 3006A(c).","start":2975.367,"stop":2990.543,"duration":15.18},{"text":"You want to carry it over from 3006A(c) to 3599.","start":2990.543,"stop":2996.53,"duration":5.99},{"text":"That -- that seems to me a little strange when they seemingly intentionally omitted it.","start":2996.53,"stop":3001.682,"duration":5.15}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't think it's strange, Justice Scalia.","start":3001.682,"stop":3004.567,"duration":2.89},{"text":"And let me explain at least my own reaction to this.","start":3004.567,"stop":3007.419,"duration":2.85},{"text":"3599, what -- the mandatory appointment requirement was cleaved from what is now 3006 -- the discretionary appointment, where Congress said in the Controlled Substances Act, look, in death cases, at trial and in habeas, we're not -- we don't want to leave it to the court's or the magistrate's discretion whether or not to appoint.","start":3007.419,"stop":3028.333,"duration":20.91},{"text":"We are appointing.","start":3028.333,"stop":3029.252,"duration":0.92},{"text":"And when it did so -- I mean, it is in essence a -- a -- a progeny -- I mean, it is -- it is a cleaving of what was a discretionary obligation.","start":3029.252,"stop":3042.425,"duration":13.17},{"text":"Congress -- Congress had no need in 3599 to reiterate the language in 30 -- 3006A(c), which itself is not limited to appointments under 3006A(c).","start":3042.425,"stop":3058.021,"duration":15.6},{"text":"I am reading from page 95 of the petition appendix.","start":3058.021,"stop":3062.673,"duration":4.65},{"text":"The statute says -- I'm sorry.","start":3062.673,"stop":3067.158,"duration":4.49},{"text":"It's page 93.","start":3067.158,"stop":3068.927,"duration":1.77},{"text":"The interests of justice standard says this -- and I'm -- it's the last sentence on page 93A --","start":3068.927,"stop":3076.181,"duration":7.25},{"text":"\"the United States magistrate judge or the Court may in the interests of justice substitute one appointed counsel for another at any stage of the proceedings. \"","start":3076.181,"stop":3087.804,"duration":11.62},{"text":"It doesn't say","start":3087.804,"stop":3088.688,"duration":0.88},{"text":"\"counsel appointed under the discretionary authority of 3006. \"","start":3088.688,"stop":3093.125,"duration":4.44},{"text":"If, like the rest of subsection (c), of which it is a part, is a general rule for duration and substitution of appointments.","start":3093.125,"stop":3102.898,"duration":9.77},{"text":"So even if it were not true that the sentence itself applied a force, it's, I think, only consistent with what Congress's manifest intention in enacting 35 -- what became 3599(e) to permit that when substitution is requested, that motion be adjudicated in light of the interests of justice.","start":3102.898,"stop":3128.281,"duration":25.38},{"text":"And indeed, that's what the State told Judge Taylor the standard was in this very case.","start":3128.281,"stop":3134.119,"duration":5.84},{"text":"I mean, look at it this way, Justice Scalia: imagine that a district court -- I realize that the cases will be few and far between.","start":3134.119,"stop":3142.891,"duration":8.77},{"text":"Very few, and very far between -- where at a late stage of the proceedings, the Court will interject substitution of counsel over the State's opposition, and over the Court's understandable desire to serve the public interest in efficiently and fairly adjudicating motions.","start":3142.891,"stop":3161.869,"duration":18.98},{"text":"But in the rare case where the district judge says, gee, I think the public interests -- I think that the interests of justice really would support putting somebody else in here, but I can't because it doesn't fit within one of the three boxes of the tests that the State ex malo has announced in its merits brief in this Court, it's just impossible to imagine that Congress would have wanted a judge to say, gee, this is one of these one in a million cases where the interests of justice really requires, but I can't do it--","start":3161.869,"stop":3198.326,"duration":36.46}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But the interests of justice is such an open-ended test.","start":3198.326,"stop":3200.761,"duration":2.43},{"text":"If that is the test, doesn't it follow that it will only be in the rarest of cases that a district judge will have been found -- will be found to have abused his or her discretion in denying a substitution request?","start":3200.761,"stop":3217.705,"duration":16.94},{"text":"Why does that very broad standard help you here?","start":3217.705,"stop":3222.274,"duration":4.57}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"--I mean, we don't -- we're not really arguing about the standard one way or the other.","start":3222.274,"stop":3228.328,"duration":6.05},{"text":"The point -- the only real question in this case is whether whatever the standard is -- and we think it has to be something like interests of justice -- but a judge in this particular situation with respect to this particular set of circumstances, there is -- my investigator, a willing percipient witness has gone to the police station and found evidence that he believes may well clear me, it requires at a minimum that the judge--","start":3228.328,"stop":3260.716,"duration":32.39}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Does your argument--","start":3260.716,"stop":3261.216,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I know you think there should be inquiry.","start":3261.216,"stop":3262.382,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"--I'm sorry?","start":3262.382,"stop":3263.382,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Before your time runs out, how would the finger -- how would the fact that there were fingerprints at the scene that do not match anybody who was known to be in that house have provided evidence for -- provided the basis for any claim that could have established Mr. Clair's innocence at this late -- at this late date, in the face of the other evidence that was present in this case: the recorded statements?","start":3263.382,"stop":3291.168,"duration":27.79}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, first of all, the other evidence in this -- the case against Mr. Clair in essence was the wired statement that he made.","start":3291.168,"stop":3298.339,"duration":7.17},{"text":"And even the trial judge in this case said only of that equivocal statement, that it was","start":3298.339,"stop":3303.826,"duration":5.49},{"text":"\"capable of being regarded as an admission. \"","start":3303.826,"stop":3306.611,"duration":2.78},{"text":"Now, we don't disagree with that.","start":3306.611,"stop":3307.828,"duration":1.22},{"text":"We're not--","start":3307.828,"stop":3308.547,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"--Did -- does your argument depend on a notion that the evidence against the defendant was weak?","start":3308.547,"stop":3314.032,"duration":5.49},{"text":"In other words, if there were a great deal of evidence against the defendant, would you be making the same argument, that the judge still had a duty to inquire?","start":3314.032,"stop":3323.307,"duration":9.27},{"text":"Or are you asking us essentially to make a determination that this was an iffy case to begin with?","start":3323.307,"stop":3328.959,"duration":5.65}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, I think the answer -- I know how frustrating this is, but I think the answer is to both -- is yes to both scenarios, particularly because there was no physical evidence linking him, and really, the State's case boiled down to this pretty confusing statement.","start":3328.959,"stop":3347.338,"duration":18.38},{"text":"It was particularly salient to say, wait a minute.","start":3347.338,"stop":3350.124,"duration":2.79},{"text":"I mean, the -- the district judge had no idea that there was any dispute about physical evidence, or any physical evidence was in the State's files that hadn't been disclosed and hadn't been--","start":3350.124,"stop":3359.746,"duration":9.62}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, suppose defense counsel had introduced at trial fingerprint evidence showing that 10 people were present at some point in that house and they weren't people who lived there.","start":3359.746,"stop":3369.536,"duration":9.79},{"text":"That's -- it's weak exculpatory evidence for the defendant at best that there were unknown people in the house.","start":3369.536,"stop":3376.524,"duration":6.99},{"text":"It might have been the cable guy.","start":3376.524,"stop":3378.357,"duration":1.83},{"text":"Who knows who they were?","start":3378.357,"stop":3379.393,"duration":1.04},{"text":"So it doesn't help very much.","start":3379.393,"stop":3380.843,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"Seth P. Waxman","textObjs":[{"text":"--Justice Alito, I mean, we are of course all arguing in a vacuum here, because we don't know what the fingerprint evidence if it were tested and run against databases would show.","start":3380.843,"stop":3391.049,"duration":10.21},{"text":"But let me give you one not at all far-fetched example: the State had -- the county coroner had determined that because of the extraordinary similarity between the murder of a woman in the neighborhood -- very close by the night before and this one, including the very peculiar puncture injuries, the coroner's report in the State's file said this is very likely the same perpetrator.","start":3391.049,"stop":3420.651,"duration":29.6},{"text":"The State has identified the perpetrator of that other crime.","start":3420.651,"stop":3425.372,"duration":4.72},{"text":"And we don't know whether even at this day the State has matched that perpetrator's fingerprints with the fingerprints that were discovered next to the victim in this case.","start":3425.372,"stop":3436.678,"duration":11.31},{"text":"And it wouldn't be far-fetched to say that in a case involving either Brady -- may I finish, it will just be this sentence -- Brady or ineffective assistance of counsel, if the fingerprint evidence did link up in that way, it certainly would go into the habeas judge's evaluation of the merits of those claims.","start":3436.678,"stop":3459.458,"duration":22.78}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel.","start":3459.458,"stop":3460.376,"duration":0.92},{"text":"Mr. Campbell, you have three minutes remaining.","start":3460.376,"stop":3462.609,"duration":2.23}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Can you tell us whether that testing has been done or not?","start":3462.609,"stop":3469.315,"duration":6.71}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I don't believe that testing has been done.","start":3469.315,"stop":3472.101,"duration":2.79}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry, no, you don't think it has been?","start":3472.101,"stop":3474.217,"duration":2.12}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I don't.","start":3474.217,"stop":3474.667,"duration":0.45},{"text":"I don't.","start":3474.667,"stop":3475.303,"duration":0.64},{"text":"The testing has not been done.","start":3475.303,"stop":3476.819,"duration":1.52},{"text":"The only testing I am aware of is the testing that's discussed in the appendix.","start":3476.819,"stop":3481.557,"duration":4.74}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"In the appendix.","start":3481.557,"stop":3482.057,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"Which excluded Mr. Goh, who apparently was the perpetrator of the other murderer, from having any DNA at the scene of the Rodgers murder.","start":3482.057,"stop":3492.948,"duration":10.89},{"text":"And Mr. Goh is dead now, so--","start":3492.948,"stop":3495.481,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry.","start":3495.481,"stop":3496.983,"duration":1.5},{"text":"Then your answer is yes, Mr. Goh's prints don't match the prints found in the file.","start":3496.983,"stop":3503.486,"duration":6.5}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"--We -- I am not aware -- the answer is, I am not -- there has been no test comparison of the fingerprints of Mr. Goh, to my -- to my knowledge, in with the -- what was found at the Rodgers murder.","start":3503.486,"stop":3518.83,"duration":15.34},{"text":"The only testing that we have is the testing that is in the appendix to the opposition to cert regarding the DNA comparisons that were done.","start":3518.83,"stop":3526.319,"duration":7.49}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"That doesn't worry your prosecutor's office?","start":3526.319,"stop":3527.902,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that the problems that the -- from the standpoint of the prosecutor's office, the -- nothing that could be found about this case would undercut the fact that Mr. Clair--","start":3527.902,"stop":3542.278,"duration":14.38}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"If the fingerprints that were found at the scene of this crime matched Goh, that wouldn't give you pause?","start":3542.278,"stop":3550.117,"duration":7.84}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"--It would -- it would certainly be a -- it would certainly -- I think it would give them pause.","start":3550.117,"stop":3555.271,"duration":5.15}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry, what?","start":3555.271,"stop":3556.271,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"I think -- I think it would give them pause, but the fact is--","start":3556.271,"stop":3560.909,"duration":4.64}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"So why hasn't the test been done?","start":3560.909,"stop":3562.642,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"--I don't know why the testing has not been done.","start":3562.642,"stop":3564.794,"duration":2.15},{"text":"But whatever the testing would be, the fact is, Mr. Clair made numerous admissions and numerous statements implicating himself in the murder of Linda -- Ms. Rodgers during the taped conversation that he had with Ms. Flores, which also corroborated Ms. Flores' testimony about his involvement in that murder.","start":3564.794,"stop":3589.592,"duration":24.8},{"text":"And that is the critical -- the critical evidence in this case.","start":3589.592,"stop":3593.13,"duration":3.54},{"text":"Now, the California Supreme Court, which has had this information in front of it, has also in fact denied already a petition based on the available evidence about the murders.","start":3593.13,"stop":3603.419,"duration":10.29},{"text":"I think also if you look--","start":3603.419,"stop":3605.954,"duration":2.54}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"You -- you don't think it's an iffy case?","start":3605.954,"stop":3607.354,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"--No, not based on that State's statement.","start":3607.354,"stop":3609.823,"duration":2.47},{"text":"The State's statements are filled with implied -- implied admissions about what he did with the jewelry, about trying to evade her questions about the case, to do anything to try to avoid having to really confront himself directly with involvement in the case.","start":3609.823,"stop":3627.115,"duration":17.29},{"text":"It's a -- it really is a very damning -- damning tape--","start":3627.115,"stop":3630.569,"duration":3.45}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"But all that's what -- what he told his girlfriend, right?","start":3630.569,"stop":3635.721,"duration":5.15},{"text":"There is nothing else.","start":3635.721,"stop":3637.24,"duration":1.52},{"text":"There is only that?","start":3637.24,"stop":3638.74,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"Ward A. Campbell","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, I think the point of it is that the tape -- she testified, and the tape corroborates her testimony.","start":3638.74,"stop":3645.244,"duration":6.5},{"text":"So in fact, what you have is -- you -- you have mutual reinforcement.","start":3645.244,"stop":3649.546,"duration":4.3}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel.","start":3649.546,"stop":3650.631,"duration":1.09},{"text":"The case is submitted.","start":3650.631,"stop":3651.681,"duration":1.05}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Roberts Court","arguedOn":"Dec 6, 2011","petitioner":"Michael Martel, Warden","respondent":"Kenneth Clair","docket":"10-1265","citation":"565 US _ (2012)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/565/10-1265","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit","grantedOn":"Jun 27, 2011","decidedOn":"Mar 5, 2012"}